body:
rustc fails to compile the code below:

```
pub trait A {
    fn a(&self);
}
struct B {
    b: i32
}
impl A for B {
    fn a(&self) {}
}

fn main() {
    let mut b = B {b: 1};
    let mut a: &mut A = &mut b;
    let ptr = std::sync::atomic::AtomicPtr::new(a);
}
```

With the error:

```
demo.rs:16:12: 16:26 error: the trait `core::marker::Sized` is not implemented for the type `A` [E0277]
demo.rs:16  let ptr = AtomicPtr::new(a);
                      ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~
demo.rs:16:12: 16:26 note: `A` does not have a constant size known at compile-time
demo.rs:16  let ptr = AtomicPtr::new(a);
                      ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~
error: aborting due to previous error
calc.git $ rustc --test demo.rs 
demo.rs:14:12: 14:45 error: the trait `core::marker::Sized` is not implemented for the type `A` [E0277]
demo.rs:14  let ptr = std::sync::atomic::AtomicPtr::new(a);
                      ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
demo.rs:14:12: 14:45 note: `A` does not have a constant size known at compile-time
demo.rs:14  let ptr = std::sync::atomic::AtomicPtr::new(a);
                      ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
error: aborting due to previous error
```

Shouldn't an atomic pointer be able to point to something with a given trait? (i.e. shouldn't the bounds on AtomicPtr be <unsized T>?)
